  <span id="freeText17765046362222656072" style="display:none">I don't generally care so much for the Confessional poets, but Snodgrass is an exception. A lot of really touching poems here, none better than the title poem - or more accurately, series of ten poems - chronicling his difficult relationship with his estranged daughter. My favorite moment is the seventh entry, which runs as follows:<br /><br />Here in the scuffled dust<br /> is our ground of play.<br />I lift you on your swing and must<br /> shove you away,<br />see you return again,<br /> drive you off again, then<br /><br />stand quiet till you come.<br /> You, though you climb<br />higher, farther from me, longer,<br /> will fall back to me stronger.<br />Bad penny, pendulum,<br /> you keep my constant time<br /><br />to bob in blue July<br /> where fat goldfinches fly<br />over the glittering, fecund<br /> reach of our growing lands.<br />Once more now, this second,<br /> I hold you in my hands.</span>
