<div id="review_1101524458" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1101524458" />
    <a title="Angie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10476804-angie"><img alt="Angie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1410333158p2/10476804.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1101524458?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angie" href="/user/show/10476804-angie">Angie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10476804-angie?shelf=poems">poems</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1101524458" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer540874297212821334">This poem was unconditionally touching. It&apos;s no wonder W.D. Snodgrass (or &quot;De&quot; as one my favorite poets, Anne Sexton, called him) won a Pulitzer for this raw - and refreshingly real - account of his divorce&apos;s effect on his and his daughter&apos;s relationship. I also have a strange affinity for compass references (not sure why? maybe something about them pointing people in the right directions?)...one is in the first section of the poem. </span>
  <span id="freeText540874297212821334" style="display:none">This poem was unconditionally touching. It's no wonder W.D. Snodgrass (or "De" as one my favorite poets, Anne Sexton, called him) won a Pulitzer for this raw - and refreshingly real - account of his divorce's effect on his and his daughter's relationship. I also have a strange affinity for compass references (not sure why? maybe something about them pointing people in the right directions?)...one is in the first section of the poem. </span>
  <a data-text-id="540874297212821334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


